column5: {50106: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50106",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to perform an SMB attack using the Responder tool, which is a type of Adversary-in-the-Middle attack. The rule looks for specific content in the network traffic that indicates the use of Responder, which positions itself between the client and server to intercept and manipulate network traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50106",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1040",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Sniffing",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may sniff network traffic to capture information about an environment, including authentication material passed over the network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Responder tool used in the detected attack is designed to perform Network Sniffing, capturing authentication material like credentials that are transmitted over the network. The Adversary-in-the-Middle position allows the tool to intercept and sniff the network traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect access to the \\\'/login.htm\\\' URI on public-facing web servers, which could indicate an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the login page to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1564", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1185",\\n    "Technique name": "Browser Session Hijacking",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may take advantage of security vulnerabilities and inherent functionality in browser software to change content, modify user-behaviors, and intercept information as part of various browser session hijacking techniques"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for access to the \\\'/login.htm\\\' URI, which could be an attempt to hijack an authenticated user\\\'s session by exploiting vulnerabilities in the login page or stealing session cookies."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {20158: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20158",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to log in to the Oracle GlassFish Server using the default administrative credentials (admin/adminadmin), which falls under the \\\'Valid Accounts\\\' technique where adversaries abuse existing credentials to gain access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20158",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "While the Snort rule specifically looks for the default administrative credentials, it could also potentially detect brute-force attempts against the Oracle GlassFish Server login page, where an adversary tries multiple username and password combinations."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {10088: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect a keylogger malware that captures user input (keystrokes) and sends the logged data via email, which aligns with the Input Capture technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1114",\\n    "Technique name": "Email Collection",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may target user email to collect sensitive information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects when the keylogger malware sends the captured data via email, which falls under the Email Collection technique where adversaries collect sensitive information from email."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {5783: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "5783",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect a keylogger, which is a type of malware that captures user input (keystrokes) to steal sensitive information like credentials. column5: {29379: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29379",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects potential exfiltration of data over an encrypted channel, which aligns with the technique of Automated Exfiltration where data is exfiltrated through automated means."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29379", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule specifically mentions detecting \\\'outbound encrypted traffic\\\', which directly relates to the Encrypted Channel technique where adversaries use encryption to conceal their command and control traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {58733: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58733",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exploit the Log4j vulnerability in Apache, which is a public-facing application. This aligns with the T1190 technique, where adversaries exploit vulnerabilities in Internet-facing systems to gain initial access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58733", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Log4j vulnerability can potentially be exploited to bypass security controls and execute arbitrary code on the target system. This relates to the T1211 technique, where adversaries exploit vulnerabilities to evade defenses."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58733",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "While the Snort rule is focused on detecting exploitation attempts on the server-side, the Log4j vulnerability can also be exploited in client applications that use the affected library. This aligns with the T1203 technique, where adversaries exploit client-side vulnerabilities to execute code."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {21318: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21318",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting malware communication over HTTP, which is an application layer protocol. column5: {60338: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60338",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a PHP webshell named DiveShell, which is a malicious server-side script that allows an attacker to execute commands on the compromised server. This aligns with the technique of abusing server software components to establish persistent access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60338",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a PHP webshell that allows an attacker to execute commands on the compromised server, which involves abusing the command and scripting interpreter (in this case, the PHP interpreter) to execute malicious commands."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60338",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound connections from the compromised server to an external network, likely for command and control purposes. column5: {49540: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49540",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1556",\\n    "Technique name": "Modify Authentication Process",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may modify authentication mechanisms and processes to access user credentials or enable otherwise unwarranted access to accounts"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to modify the WordPress user roles configuration, which could potentially allow an adversary to modify the authentication process and gain unauthorized access to accounts with elevated privileges."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49540", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1484",\\n    "Technique name": "Domain Policy Modification",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may modify the configuration settings of a domain to evade defenses and/or escalate privileges in domain environments"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "While the Snort rule specifically targets WordPress, modifying user roles and privileges can be considered a form of policy modification within the context of the WordPress domain, which could allow an adversary to escalate privileges or evade defenses."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37313: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exfiltrate data over the SMTP protocol, which could be used as a command and control channel by adversaries."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1030",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Transfer Size Limits",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "An adversary may exfiltrate data in fixed size chunks instead of whole files or limit packet sizes below certain thresholds"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for specific patterns in the data being exfiltrated, which could indicate that the data is being split into smaller chunks or packets to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {23612: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23612",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1221",\\n    "Technique name": "Template Injection",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to embed JavaScript code within an XML template in a PDF file, which aligns with the technique of Template Injection where adversaries modify document templates to conceal malicious code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "23612", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to execute JavaScript code within a PDF file, which could potentially be achieved by exploiting a vulnerability in the PDF viewer application, aligning with the Exploitation for Client Execution technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38890: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38890",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect exfiltration attempts by the Win.Trojan.Kirts malware, which is specifically mentioned in the rule message. The rule looks for HTTP requests containing specific patterns that indicate data exfiltration, such as the presence of \\\'fname=Hawkeye_Keylogger\\\' and \\\'&data=\\\' in the URI. column5: {50467: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1003",\\n    "Technique name": "OS Credential Dumping",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the use of Mimikatz, a tool commonly used for credential dumping on Windows systems. Mimikatz allows adversaries to extract plaintext passwords, hashes, and other credential material from memory, which aligns with the T1003 technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1555",\\n    "Technique name": "Credentials from Password Stores",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may search for common password storage locations to obtain user credentials"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "Mimikatz, the tool detected by the Snort rule, can be used to extract credentials from various password stores on Windows systems, including the Windows Credential Manager, which is relevant to the T1555 technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59218: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59218",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Server Software Component\\\', \\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound connections from a web shell named C99Madnet, which is a PHP-based web shell that allows adversaries to execute commands on the compromised server. This web shell abuses the legitimate PHP server software to establish persistent access, which aligns with the T1505 technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59218",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Exploit Public-Facing Application\\\', \\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The presence of a web shell like C99Madnet on a server suggests that the adversary may have exploited a vulnerability in a public-facing web application to gain initial access and upload the web shell, which is consistent with the T1190 technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {52081: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "52081",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique Name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule appears to be detecting an attempt to perform a Responder poisoner service negotiation attack, which is a type of Adversary-in-the-Middle attack where the adversary positions themselves between the client and server to intercept and manipulate network traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "52081", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1558",\\n    "Technique Name": "Steal or Forge Kerberos Tickets",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to subvert Kerberos authentication by stealing or forging Kerberos tickets to enable Pass the Ticket"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Responder poisoner service negotiation attack detected by the Snort rule is a technique used to steal or forge Kerberos tickets, which can then be used for lateral movement and privilege escalation within a network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {16125: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16125",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique Name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the retrieval of a file named \\\'k3ylogger.txt\\\', which suggests the presence of a keylogger malware that captures user input, such as keystrokes, to steal credentials or sensitive information."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16125",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1005",\\n    "Technique Name": "Data from Local System",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for the retrieval of a file named \\\'k3ylogger.txt\\\', which implies that the adversary is attempting to access and potentially exfiltrate data from the local system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16125",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique Name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is triggered when the file \\\'k3ylogger.txt\\\' is retrieved over an FTP connection, which could be used as a command and control channel for exfiltrating the captured data."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {22061: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malicious IFRAME load attempt, which is a common technique used in drive-by compromise attacks where malicious code is injected into a website and executed when a user visits the compromised site."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1659",\\n    "Technique name": "Content Injection",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may gain access and continuously communicate with victims by injecting malicious content into systems through online network traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting an attempt to inject a malicious IFRAME into a website, which is a form of content injection used by adversaries to gain access and communicate with victims."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {30521: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30521",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exploit the OpenSSL TLSv1 heartbeat read overrun vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160) in public-facing servers, which aligns with the technique of exploiting public-facing applications to gain initial access to a network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30521",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "While the primary focus of the rule is detecting the initial exploitation attempt, a successful exploitation could potentially lead to the adversary gaining access to internal systems by exploiting other remote services, making this technique relevant."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56616: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56616",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Application Layer Protocol\\\', \\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for HTTP POST requests to specific paths, which indicates the use of an application layer protocol (HTTP) for communication, likely for command and control purposes."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56616", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Proxy\\\', \\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for outbound connections to external networks, which could potentially be proxied connections used by adversaries to communicate with their command and control infrastructure."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol, potentially used by adversaries to blend in with normal traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for a specific pattern in the HTTP Cookie header, which could be indicative of data exfiltration over the command and control channel established using the application layer protocol."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1132",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Encoding",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may encode data to make the content of command and control traffic more difficult to detect"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is using a PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expression) to match a specific pattern in the HTTP Cookie header, which could be an encoded form of data used by adversaries to obfuscate the command and control traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42834: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42834",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect a web shell connection, which is a type of malicious server software component that allows an attacker to gain persistent access to a system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42834",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically looking for a web shell connection, which is a type of malicious web service that can be used to relay data to and from a compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42834",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1567",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service to exfiltrate data rather than their primary command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The web shell connection detected by the Snort rule could potentially be used for data exfiltration over a web service, rather than a traditional command and control channel."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56615: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for HTTP traffic with specific patterns, which indicates the use of an application layer protocol (HTTP) for communication, potentially by an adversary to blend in with normal traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56615", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1095",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use an OSI non-application layer protocol for communication between host and C2 server or among infected hosts within a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule is specifically looking for HTTP traffic, the technique of using non-application layer protocols is relevant as adversaries may attempt to use other protocols to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific patterns in the HTTP traffic, which could be an attempt to detect encrypted or obfuscated command and control traffic within the HTTP protocol."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {16573: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16573",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects obfuscated ActiveX object instantiation via the unescape function, which is a technique used to obfuscate code or data. column5: {59929: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique Name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to download a JSP webshell named \\\'Behinder\\\', which is a capability that can be used by adversaries for further malicious activities on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique Name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for a specific pattern in HTTP traffic, which suggests that the adversary is attempting to exploit a vulnerability in a public-facing web application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique Name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The JSP webshell \\\'Behinder\\\' is a type of script that can be executed on the server to run arbitrary commands, which aligns with the technique of abusing command and scripting interpreters."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {39755: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39755",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects the use of PowerShell commands, which is a command and scripting interpreter on Windows systems. column5: {33942: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33942",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the download of a .cpl (Control Panel) file, which could potentially be a malicious tool or payload being transferred into the target environment."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33942",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically excludes certain legitimate .cpl files, suggesting that the adversary may be attempting to masquerade their malicious payload as a legitimate Control Panel file."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33942",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the PK|03 04| header, which is indicative of a ZIP file. column5: {38724: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38724",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malware that has keylogging and clipboard logging capabilities, which are methods of capturing user input to obtain sensitive information like credentials or other data."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38724", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1115",\\n    "Technique name": "Clipboard Data",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may collect data stored in the clipboard from users copying information within or between applications"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule specifically mentions \\\'Clipboard-Logger Enabled\\\', indicating that the malware has the capability to collect data from the clipboard, which is a technique used by adversaries to gather sensitive information."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38724",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound communication from the malware, likely to a command and control server, which suggests that the malware may be exfiltrating the collected data (keystrokes, clipboard data) over this channel."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {58738: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58738",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exploit the Log4j vulnerability in Apache web servers, which are public-facing applications accessible from the internet. column5: {13480: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "13480",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect a keylogger malware called \\\'FindNot GuardDog\\\', which captures user input (keystrokes) to steal credentials or sensitive information, aligning with the T1056 Input Capture technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "13480",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1114",\\n    "Technique name": "Email Collection",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may target user email to collect sensitive information"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is triggered when the malware attempts to send captured data via email (SMTP protocol), which falls under the T1114 Email Collection technique, where adversaries collect sensitive information from user emails."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56862: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP POST requests with specific content, which indicates the use of the HTTP application layer protocol for communication, potentially by malware."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for specific content in HTTP POST requests, which could be an indication of data exfiltration over the command and control channel established by the malware."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1567",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service to exfiltrate data rather than their primary command and control channel"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting HTTP POST requests, which could be an attempt by the malware to exfiltrate data over a web service, potentially to avoid detection by traditional command and control channels."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50104: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50104",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an SMB negotiation attack attempt, which is a type of adversary-in-the-middle attack where the attacker positions themselves between the client and server to intercept and manipulate network traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50104",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1040",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Sniffing",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may sniff network traffic to capture information about an environment, including authentication material passed over the network"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The adversary-in-the-middle attack detected by the Snort rule could be used for network sniffing, allowing the attacker to capture sensitive information like authentication credentials from the network traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48532: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48532",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1220",\\n    "Technique name": "XSL Script Processing",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may bypass application control and obscure execution of code by embedding scripts inside XSL files"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to bypass the VBScript execution policy in Internet Explorer 11 by using XSL script processing. This aligns with the T1220 technique, which describes how adversaries can embed scripts within XSL files to bypass application control and execute code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48532", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Internet Explorer 11 to execute code, which aligns with the T1203 technique of exploiting client application vulnerabilities for code execution."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47461: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47461",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to execute PowerShell commands, which is a command and scripting interpreter on Windows systems. This aligns with the technique of abusing command and script interpreters to execute malicious code."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47461", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1068",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Privilege Escalation",\\n    "Quotes": [\\n      "Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in an attempt to elevate privileges"\\n    ],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule mentions \\\'CTSWebProxy ActiveX privilege escalation attempt\\\', which suggests that the detected activity is related to exploiting a vulnerability in the CTSWebProxy ActiveX control to escalate privileges, aligning with the \\\'Exploitation for Privilege Escalation\\\' technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}
